    We had a remarkable experience at La Maison Arabe. We were welcome by a friendly staff, offered tea and a place to sit for a short lecture. We then took a walk to a nearby "public oven". It was very interesting. Once we returned to the building where our class was to be held we were directed to the room that would be our cooking class room. The kitchen setup was jaw-dropping. Each student had a very comfortable space which included a small stove top, sink, waste can, utensils, pans, a shared television monitor for watching the teacher at the front of the room, ingredients, spices and everything we needed to complete our tagine. The lesson began with bread making and everyone was given an opportunity to go up and "knead" the bread along side the teacher. From there we began our lemon chicken and olive tagine. It was so much fun! After the cooking was complete a group lunch was shared (which we were unable to attend) along with each individual's creation. I hope I have an opportunity to return to La Maison Arabe for another class in the future. If in Marrakech, I would highly recommend La Maison for a very thorough and informative class on Moroccan cuisine. Thank you to the very friendly staff who went out of their way to provide a fun and instructive class.

    So I came back to stay in a place that is a fairy tale, which has a particular history and which retains a strong Moroccan identity.
    La Maison Arabe, a luxury hotel in the heart of the old city, was the first restaurant in the Medina opened to foreigners in the 1940s and then, in the 1990s, the first boutique riad-hotel in Marrakech.
    A place of timeless beauty that still maintains the aristocratic splendor of a traditional Riad but which offers all the comforts and luxury services, where Ernest Hemingway, Jackie Kennedy and Rita Hayworth came for dinner, and where even Sir Winston Churchill slept.

    Medina

    Hammam bath houses and covered spice and textile souks line the maze of cobblestoned lanes in the Medina, which occupies Marrakesh’s original fortified citadel. At night, Jemaa el-Fna square teems with snake charmers, folk dancers, and street food vendors serving all manner of food. Bahia Palace and Le Jardin Secret are 19th-century complexes open to the public, with ornate courtyards, mosaics, and gardens.

    About this hotel

    This upmarket hotel in an elegant riad is a 14-minute walk from Jemaa el-Fnaa square and 2 km from Majorelle Garden. …

    Featuring ornate decor, the sophisticated, individually styled rooms and suites offer free Wi-Fi, satellite TV, safes and minibars. Some have sitting areas, fireplaces and/or terraces.

    Shuttle service to a nearby country club is complimentary. Other amenities include a piano bar, 2 restaurants and a cooking school, plus a boutique and a garden. There's also 2 outdoor pools (1 is off-site), a furnished terrace and a spa with 2 hammams. Breakfast, parking and an airport shuttle are available. Children age 5 and over are welcome.
